foia:ProcessedRequestSection.foia:FootnoteText: OCFO-CAM has been changed to CAM.

The discrepancy in the number of pending requests in beginning of fiscal year for the components is due to how cases are tracked within our case management system. Example: a request initially assigned to Office "A" in FY15 is later assigned to Office "B" would show as a pending case for Office "A" at the end of FY15, but when Office "B" closes the case in FY16, the report will show Office "B" as the pending office at the start of FY15 rather than Office "A".

foia:ProcessedAppealSection.foia:FootnoteText: The discrepancy in the number of pending appeals in beginning of fiscal year for the components is due to how cases are tracked within our case management system. Example: an appeal initially assigned to Office "A" in FY15 is later assigned to Office "B" would show as a pending appeal for Office "A" at the end of FY15, but when Office "B" closes the appeal in FY16, the report will show Office "B" as the pending office at the start of FY15 rather than Office "A".

foia:PersonnelAndCostSection.foia:FootnoteText: M represents Multiple Offices assigned, therefore their personnel are captured under the individual offices data.

foia:FeesCollectedSection.foia:FootnoteText: Agency total Fees Collected reflects amount collected in FY16. This includes fees collected from prior year, closed cases.

foia:ProcessedRequestComparisonSection.foia:FootnoteText: The discrepancy in the number of requests received during last year and the number of requests processed during last year is due to how cases are tracked within our case management system. Example: a request received initially assigned to Office "A" in FY15 is later assigned to Office "B" would show as a request received for Office "A" at the end of FY15, but when Office "B" closes the case in FY16, the report will show Office "B" as the request received office at the start of FY15 rather than Office "A".

foia:ProcessedAppealComparisonSection.foia:FootnoteText: The discrepancy in the number of appeals received during last year and the number of appeals processed during last year is due to how cases are tracked within our case management system. Example: an appeal received initially assigned to Office "A" in FY15 is later assigned to Office "B" would show as an appeal received for Office "A" at the end of FY15, but when Office "B" closes the case in FY16, the report will show Office "B" as the appeal received office at the start of FY15 rather than Office "A".
